    <section class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <details>
        <summary>Why did stocks surge after Powell rebuffed Trump?</summary>
        <p>Historically, the stock market reacts positively when the Federal Reserve Chairman pushes back against political pressure, such as demands from the President to lower interest rates. This is because Wall Street views Fed independence as crucial for long-term economic stability, preventing short-term political manipulation of the economy.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Can the President fire the Federal Reserve Chairman?</summary>
        <p>The legal consensus is that the President cannot simply fire the Federal Reserve Chairman over policy disagreements. The Federal Reserve Act states that Governors (including the Chair) can only be removed 'for cause,' which generally implies a legal or ethical violation, not a difference of opinion on interest rates.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>What is the Federal Reserve's Dual Mandate?</summary>
        <p>The Federal Reserve's Dual Mandate refers to its two primary goals set by Congress: maximizing employment and stabilizing prices (managing inflation). The Fed uses monetary policy tools, like adjusting interest rates, to balance these two often-competing objectives.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>Why does Donald Trump criticize Jerome Powell?</summary>
        <p>During his presidency, Donald Trump frequently criticized Fed Chair Jerome Powell, arguing that the Fed was keeping interest rates too high, which Trump believed restricted economic growth and hampered the stock market's potential. Presidents generally prefer lower interest rates to boost the economy during their term.</p>
      </details>

      <details>
        <summary>How do interest rates affect the stock market?</summary>
        <p>Interest rates essentially set the 'price of money.' When the Fed lowers rates, borrowing becomes cheaper for businesses (boosting profits) and consumers (boosting spending), which typically causes stock prices to rise. Conversely, higher rates make borrowing expensive and offer investors safer yield alternatives (like bonds), which can cool down the stock market.</p>
      </details>

    </section>
